                <div class="post-text-block">
                    <i>A Hologram For The King</i> was not as advertised.
                    The first two-thirds of the novel focus on the background of the
                    washed-out protagonist, Alan Clay. Clay, down on his luck, is a
                    middle-aged business man who has not seen personal success for the
                    last 20 years. In extraordinary debt, Clay bets his livelihood and
                    daughter’s future on his ability to negotiate a deal between King
                    Abdullah and Reliant Energy.<br>
                    <br>
                    Despite the many positive reviews for this novel, I found the
                    development of the main character and plot lacking. For a novel focusing
                    on the development of a singular character, I was dismayed to find very few
                    of Alan Clay's traits sympathizable. Instead of heralding a powerful message,
                    he seemed to invite skepticism and criticism. In lieu of representing businessman
                    who came into maturity with outdated business practices, Alan Clay seemed
                    to represent an unassertive character who was unable to react to changes to the status
                    quo, unable to consider issues of the future, and unwilling to bolster his
                    skillset.
                </div>
