                <div class="post-text-block">
                    After reading <i>Anna Karenina</i>, I can see how the novel came to be
                    known as one of the best works of fiction of all time. Set in the
                    1860s and 1870s, Anna Karenina juxtaposes the lives of its two main
                    characters, Konstantin Levin and Anna Karenina. Levin, a farmer,
                    writer, and intellectual, spends the novel simultaneously seeking
                    marriage with the love of his life, Kitty, and rigorously attempting
                    to uncover the meaning of life. Anna, in contrast, originally an
                    admired and beautiful woman of society, spends her time unsuccessfully
                    attempting to maintain a front of propriety while engaging in an affair
                    with a bachelor, Count Alexei Vronsky.<br>
                    <br>
                    Tolstoy’s unique ability to peer into the mind of his characters
                    and realistically describe their every thought and emotion makes
                    the juxtaposition of these two characters both riveting and timeless.
                    <i>Anna Karenina</i> made me rethink my understanding of humanity, how
                    the world works, and the justice of everything. Though well worth
                    the time, if you choose to tackle this novel, buckle up. Over 700
                    pages of dense reading, <i>Anna Karenina</i> is not for the faint of heart
                    and will, without a doubt, challenge the hardiest of reading stamina.
                </div>
